PDB is VERY important exactly in the node drain / upgrade situation you described. â€œDuring voluntary disruptions (like drain, upgrade), how many pods are allowed to go down at a time.â€

It protects your application from downtime.

apiVersion: policy/v1
kind: PodDisruptionBudget
metadata:
  name: app-pdb
  namespace: default
spec:
  minAvailable: 1
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      app: my-app
-----------------------------
âŒ PDB mhanje â€œpod old node var chaluch pahijeâ€ asa nahi

âœ… PDB mhanje â€œcluster madhe kamit kami 1 pod running pahijeâ€

Pod:

Old node var asu shakto

Kinva new node var asu shakto
================
PDB ensures that during node draining, Kubernetes evicts pods gradually so that the minimum required pods remain available, enabling zero-downtime upgrades.
===============================================
ðŸ”¹ Commands to test PDB behavior
# kubectl get pdb -A
# kubectl describe pdb app-pdb
